Police recovered the bodies of the family who were kidnapped at their homestead on Monday 2 December. The three family members 71 year old gogo together with  16 and 17 year old grand daughters from Lower Tsojana Village, Hello in the Eastern Cape were last seen on Sunday night. A search was conducted and the bodies were seen by the shepherd  floating in the river near Mhlahlane River on Saturday 7 December. Police were summoned and divers were called and managed to take out the bodies. Bodies were found tight  with chains. Report from the 19 year old sister who has not been living with them suggests that the two dead sisters were being raped over time by their uncle. This included herself until one of them fell pregnant. She then reported the matter to the police and a case of rape was registered. On the day of the missing family, the police had earlier visited the family as part of the investigation after rape allegations were reported. It is alleged that after the police left, the uncle arrived and began questioning the family on what the police were looking for. That was the last time both the family and the uncle were seen. Police spokeswoman Captain Namhla Mdleleni said three cases of murder and kidnapping were opened and no arrest yet. "Police are appealing to anyone who can assist with the information that can lead to the arrest of the perpetrators  to please contact toll free number 0860010111," she said. 